Skywave — live DSC monitor
==========================

A browser-native view onto the routine maritime radio traffic almost
nobody reads anymore. Skywave picks dozens of public KiwiSDRs around
the world, tunes each to one of the six international Digital Selective
Calling channels (MF 2187.5 kHz and five HF frequencies), decodes every
burst, dedupes across receivers, and prints the result as a scrolling
table of who's calling whom, from where, about what.

Two deployments share the same UI:

* **v1 (client-decoded)** — every browser opens its own fleet of
  WebSockets to the KiwiSDR pool and runs the decoder locally. Still
  live in `client/`.

* **v2 (edge-decoded, slot-shared)** — one Cloudflare Durable Object
  per KiwiSDR channel holds the only upstream WebSocket, runs the
  decoder, and fans decoded calls to every browser attached to it.
  One listener on each channel, forever, serving everyone who turns
  up. See `PLAN.md` for the full design and `worker/src/` for the
  code.


Using it
--------

Open the page. It asks the gateway for a rack of receivers covering
the DSC channels (constrained to the selected region) and subscribes
to each. The top-right dropdown narrows the scan — NW Europe, the
Mediterranean, US East Coast, etc.

Audio stays silent between transmissions. When a DSC FSK burst is
detected on one of the receivers we're listening to, the strongest
signal gets routed to your speakers — so you hear the actual tones of
the protocol the first time it happens, which is the fun bit.

Click a row to expand: decoder internals, the full list of receivers
that heard the call, and a mini-map showing where those receivers sit
along with the vessel's last known position.

Vessel enrichment uses Global Fishing Watch's public search + tracks
endpoints, proxied through the Cloudflare Worker. Ship name, flag,
type, callsign, IMO and a decimated 14-day AIS track come back
automatically for every MMSI that GFW has data on. No API key needed.


Etiquette
---------

Public KiwiSDR receivers have a limited number of user slots. In v2
the Worker holds exactly one connection per channel per receiver —
`ident_user=skywave shared listener` — no matter how many humans are
viewing. A ReceiverDO tears itself down five minutes after the last
subscriber disconnects, so a quiet region stops squatting slots.


Repo layout
-----------

    client/            static site (Pages / any HTTP server)
      index.html       entry point; Leaflet + JetBrains Mono + the app
      styles.css       the whole stylesheet, mobile-first
      app.js           v2 viewer: rack subscription, rendering, audio
      vessels.js       GFW vessel identity lookup
      regions.js       DSC channels, regional presets, MID→ISO
      map.js           per-card mini map (Leaflet)
      favicon.svg      Data Desk mark
    worker/            Cloudflare Worker + Durable Objects
      wrangler.toml    DO bindings + migrations
      src/
        index.js       router: v1 legacy routes + v2 /v2/rack, /v2/slot
        directory-do.js  rack composer + receiver-list refresh
        receiver-do.js   per-channel KiwiSDR listener + decoder + fanout
        kiwi-upstream.js server-side KiwiSDR WS client
        dsc.js           ITU-R M.493 decoder (same as v1)
        regions.js       server-side subset of regions
        location-hint.js GPS → Cloudflare locationHint
    PLAN.md            the v2 design document


Local development
-----------------

The client is pure static ES modules; any HTTP server does it:

    cd client && python3 -m http.server 8000

The gateway needs wrangler:

    cd worker && npx wrangler dev
    # or: npx wrangler deploy

Point `index.html`'s `<meta name="skywave-gateway">` at your wrangler-
dev URL (e.g. `http://127.0.0.1:8787`) if you want local end-to-end.

Add `?debug=1` to the page URL for verbose console logging.


Credits & research
------------------

Decoder ported from the Data Desk research repo at
`~/Research/dsc-triangulation`. Original Python reference:
`scripts/dsc_decode_ddesk.py`. Canonical .NET reference:
`vendor/TAOSW.DSC_Decoder.Core/GMDSSDecoder.cs`.
